# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dataclasses-json
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] In computer science, a **data structure** is a way to organize and store data that is usually chosen for efficient access to data.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] More precisely, a data structure is the physical implementation of a data type, including specifications of the data organization and storage format, as well functions or operations for working with this data.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] Data structures are closely related to abstract data types (ADTs).
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] The data structure describes the representation of data in memory and how operations are carried out, while the ADT describes the logical form or algebraic structure of the data type—what operations are allowed and what results they produce—without describing how those operations are implemented.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] Some authors do not use the term "abstract data type" and simply refer to the logical and physical forms of the data structure.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] Efficient data structures are essential for managing large datasets and are fundamental to algorithm design.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] Relational databases commonly use B-tree indice for data retrieval, while compiler implementations usually use hash tables to look up identifiers.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] Filesystems and search engines make extensive use of specialized data structures.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] Rob Pike has stated that the choice of data structure almost always has a greater impact on efficiency than the choice of algorithm, as the algorithm is often self-evident.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] Data structures are used to organize data in both primary memory (RAM) and secondary storage (such as disks).
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] Implementing a data structure involves writing a set of subroutines—such as insertion, deletion, traversal, or lookup—that create and manipulate instances of that structure.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] Data structures can be implemented using a variety of programming languages and techniques.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] A data structure corresponds directly to a single concrete implementation, in contrast to an ADT which describes behavior and operations independently of any particular implementation.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] There may be multiple concrete data structures for the same ADT, for example a linked list or a resizable array for the list ADT.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] As such, the efficiency of a data structure is closely tied to its concrete implementation, and must be evaluated through benchmarks and theoretical simulation.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] Data structures generally rely on the ability of a computer to store and access data via memory addresses (as specified by a pointer—a bit string—or more abstractly via references) that can be itself stored in memory and manipulated by the program.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] For example, arrays and records store elements in contiguous memory locations, requiring a rigid layout but allowing fast indexed access by computing the address through arithmetic operations.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] In contrast, linked data structures (such as linked lists and trees) store addresses of related elements within their structure, enabling flexible memory usage and dynamic resizing.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] These different methods of data structuring come with different tradeoffs and are suited to different tasks.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] For instance, the contiguous memory allocation in arrays facilitates rapid access and modification operations, leading to optimized performance in sequential data processing scenarios.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] There are numerous types of data structures, generally built upon simpler primitive data types.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] Most assembly languages and some low-level languages, such as BCPL (Basic Combined Programming Language), lack built-in support for data structures.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] On the other hand, many high-level programming languages and some higher-level assembly languages, such as MASM, have special syntax or other built-in support for certain data structures, such as records and arrays.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] For example, the C (a direct descendant of BCPL) and Pascal languages support structs and records, respectively, in addition to vectors (one-dimensional arrays) and multi-dimensional arrays.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] Most programming languages feature some sort of library mechanism that allows data structure implementations to be reused by different programs.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] Modern languages usually come with standard libraries that implement the most common data structures.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] Examples are the C++ Standard Template Library, the Java Collections Framework, and the Microsoft .NET Framework.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] Modern languages also generally support modular programming, the separation between the interface of a library module and its implementation.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] Some provide opaque data types that allow clients to hide implementation details.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] Object-oriented programming languages, such as C++, Java, and Smalltalk, typically use classes for this purpose.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-structure] Many known data structures have concurrent versions which allow multiple computing threads to access a single concrete instance of a data structure simultaneously.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-transfer-object] In the field of programming a **data transfer object** (**DTO**) is an object that carries data between processes.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-transfer-object] The motivation for its use is that communication between processes is usually done resorting to remote interfaces (e.g., web services), where each call is an expensive operation.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-transfer-object] The difference between data transfer objects and business objects or data access objects is that a DTO does not have any behavior except for storage, retrieval, serialization and deserialization of its own data (mutators, accessors, serializers and parsers).
[src:dataclasses-json/data-transfer-object] In other words, DTOs are simple objects that should not contain any business logic but may contain serialization and deserialization mechanisms for transferring data over the wire.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-transfer-object] This pattern is often incorrectly used outside of remote interfaces.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-transfer-object] This has triggered a response from its author where he reiterates that the whole purpose of DTOs is to shift data in expensive remote calls.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-transfer-object] The two terms have been conflated by Sun/Java community in the past.
[src:dataclasses-json/data-transfer-object] For the model–view–viewmodel pattern, the data transfer object can be referred to as the viewmodel.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] This module provides a decorator and functions for automatically adding generated special methods such as `__init__()` and `__repr__()` to user-defined classes.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] It was originally described in **PEP 557**.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] The member variables to use in these generated methods are defined using **PEP 526** type annotations.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Note that this method is automatically added to the class: it is not directly specified in the `InventoryItem` definition shown above.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] This function is a decorator that is used to add generated special methods to classes, as described below.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] The `@dataclass` decorator examines the class to find `field`s.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] A `field` is defined as a class variable that has a type annotation.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] With two exceptions described below, nothing in `@dataclass` examines the type specified in the variable annotation.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] The order of the fields in all of the generated methods is the order in which they appear in the class definition.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] The `@dataclass` decorator will add various “dunder” methods to the class, described below.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] If any of the added methods already exist in the class, the behavior depends on the parameter, as documented below.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] The decorator returns the same class that it is called on; no new class is created.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] If `@dataclass` is used just as a simple decorator with no parameters, it acts as if it has the default values documented in this signature.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] `TypeError` will be raised if a field without a default value follows a field with a default value.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] This is true whether this occurs in a single class, or as a result of class inheritance.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] For common and simple use cases, no other functionality is required.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] There are, however, some dataclass features that require additional per-field information.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] To satisfy this need for additional information, you can replace the default field value with a call to the provided `field()` function.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] As shown above, the `MISSING` value is a sentinel object used to detect if some parameters are provided by the user.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] This sentinel is used because `None` is a valid value for some parameters with a distinct meaning.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] No code should directly use the `MISSING` value.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] If the default value of a field is specified by a call to `field()`, then the class attribute for this field will be replaced by the specified *default* value.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] If *default* is not provided, then the class attribute will be deleted.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] The intent is that after the `@dataclass` decorator runs, the class attributes will all contain the default values for the fields, just as if the default value itself were specified.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] The class attribute `C.z` will be `10`, the class attribute `C.t` will be `20`, and the class attributes `C.x` and `C.y` will not be set.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] `Field` objects describe each defined field.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] These objects are created internally, and are returned by the `fields()` module-level method (see below).
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Users should never instantiate a `Field` object directly.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Other attributes may exist, but they are private and must not be inspected or relied on.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] `InitVar[T]` type annotations describe variables that are init-only.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Fields annotated with `InitVar` are considered pseudo-fields, and thus are neither returned by the `fields()` function nor used in any way except adding them as parameters to `__init__()` and an optional `__post_init__()`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Returns a tuple of `Field` objects that define the fields for this dataclass.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Accepts either a dataclass, or an instance of a dataclass.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Raises `TypeError` if not passed a dataclass or instance of one.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Does not return pseudo-fields which are `ClassVar` or `InitVar`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Converts the dataclass *obj* to a dict (by using the factory function *dict_factory*).
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Each dataclass is converted to a dict of its fields, as `name: value` pairs. dataclasses, dicts, lists, and tuples are recursed into.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Other objects are copied with `copy.deepcopy()`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] `asdict()` raises `TypeError` if *obj* is not a dataclass instance.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Converts the dataclass *obj* to a tuple (by using the factory function *tuple_factory*).
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Each dataclass is converted to a tuple of its field values. dataclasses, dicts, lists, and tuples are recursed into.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] `astuple()` raises `TypeError` if *obj* is not a dataclass instance.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Creates a new dataclass with name *cls_name*, fields as defined in *fields*, base classes as given in *bases*, and initialized with a namespace as given in *namespace*.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] *fields* is an iterable whose elements are each either `name`, `(name, type)`, or `(name, type, Field)`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] If just `name` is supplied, `typing.Any` is used for `type`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] The values of *init*, *repr*, *eq*, *order*, *unsafe_hash*, *frozen*, *match_args*, *kw_only*, *slots*, and *weakref_slot* have the same meaning as they do in `@dataclass`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] If *module* is defined, the `__module__` attribute of the dataclass is set to that value.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] By default, it is set to the module name of the caller.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] The *decorator* parameter is a callable that will be used to create the dataclass.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] It should take the class object as a first argument and the same keyword arguments as `@dataclass`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] By default, the `@dataclass` function is used.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] This function is not strictly required, because any Python mechanism for creating a new class with `__annotations__` can then apply the `@dataclass` function to convert that class to a dataclass.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] This function is provided as a convenience.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Added in version 3.14: Added the *decorator* parameter.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Creates a new object of the same type as *obj*, replacing fields with values from *changes*.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] If *obj* is not a Data Class, raises `TypeError`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] If keys in *changes* are not field names of the given dataclass, raises `TypeError`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] The newly returned object is created by calling the `__init__()` method of the dataclass.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] This ensures that `__post_init__()`, if present, is also called.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Init-only variables without default values, if any exist, must be specified on the call to `replace()` so that they can be passed to `__init__()` and `__post_init__()`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] It is an error for *changes* to contain any fields that are defined as having `init=False`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] A `ValueError` will be raised in this case.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Be forewarned about how `init=False` fields work during a call to `replace()`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] They are not copied from the source object, but rather are initialized in `__post_init__()`, if they’re initialized at all.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] It is expected that `init=False` fields will be rarely and judiciously used.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] If they are used, it might be wise to have alternate class constructors, or perhaps a custom `replace()` (or similarly named) method which handles instance copying.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Dataclass instances are also supported by generic function `copy.replace()`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Return `True` if its parameter is a dataclass (including subclasses of a dataclass, but not including generic aliases) or an instance of one, otherwise return `False`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] A sentinel value signifying a missing default or default_factory.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] A sentinel value used as a type annotation.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Any fields after a pseudo-field with the type of `KW_ONLY` are marked as keyword-only fields.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Note that a pseudo-field of type `KW_ONLY` is otherwise completely ignored.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] By convention, a name of `_` is used for a `KW_ONLY` field.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Keyword-only fields signify `__init__()` parameters that must be specified as keywords when the class is instantiated.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] In a single dataclass, it is an error to specify more than one field whose type is `KW_ONLY`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Raised when an implicitly defined `__setattr__()` or `__delattr__()` is called on a dataclass which was defined with `frozen=True`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] When defined on the class, it will be called by the generated `__init__()`, normally as `self.__post_init__()`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] However, if any `InitVar` fields are defined, they will also be passed to `__post_init__()` in the order they were defined in the class.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] If no `__init__()` method is generated, then `__post_init__()` will not automatically be called.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Among other uses, this allows for initializing field values that depend on one or more other fields.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] The `__init__()` method generated by `@dataclass` does not call base class `__init__()` methods.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Note, however, that in general the dataclass-generated `__init__()` methods don’t need to be called, since the derived dataclass will take care of initializing all fields of any base class that is a dataclass itself.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] See the section below on init-only variables for ways to pass parameters to `__post_init__()`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Also see the warning about how `replace()` handles `init=False` fields.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] One of the few places where `@dataclass` actually inspects the type of a field is to determine if a field is a class variable as defined in **PEP 526**.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] It does this by checking if the type of the field is `typing.ClassVar`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] If a field is a `ClassVar`, it is excluded from consideration as a field and is ignored by the dataclass mechanisms.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Such `ClassVar` pseudo-fields are not returned by the module-level `fields()` function.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Another place where `@dataclass` inspects a type annotation is to determine if a field is an init-only variable.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] It does this by seeing if the type of a field is of type `InitVar`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] If a field is an `InitVar`, it is considered a pseudo-field called an init-only field.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] As it is not a true field, it is not returned by the module-level `fields()` function.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Init-only fields are added as parameters to the generated `__init__()` method, and are passed to the optional `__post_init__()` method.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] They are not otherwise used by dataclasses.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] In this case, `fields()` will return `Field` objects for `i` and `j`, but not for `database`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] It is not possible to create truly immutable Python objects.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] However, by passing `frozen=True` to the `@dataclass` decorator you can emulate immutability.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] In that case, dataclasses will add `__setattr__()` and `__delattr__()` methods to the class.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] These methods will raise a `FrozenInstanceError` when invoked.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] There is a tiny performance penalty when using `frozen=True`: `__init__()` cannot use simple assignment to initialize fields, and must use `object.__setattr__()`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] When the dataclass is being created by the `@dataclass` decorator, it looks through all of the class’s base classes in reverse MRO (that is, starting at `object`) and, for each dataclass that it finds, adds the fields from that base class to an ordered mapping of fields.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] After all of the base class fields are added, it adds its own fields to the ordered mapping.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] All of the generated methods will use this combined, calculated ordered mapping of fields.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Because the fields are in insertion order, derived classes override base classes.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] The final list of fields is, in order, `x`, `y`, `z`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] The final type of `x` is `int`, as specified in class `C`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] After the parameters needed for `__init__()` are computed, any keyword-only parameters are moved to come after all regular (non-keyword-only) parameters.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] This is a requirement of how keyword-only parameters are implemented in Python: they must come after non-keyword-only parameters.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Note that the parameters have been re-ordered from how they appear in the list of fields: parameters derived from regular fields are followed by parameters derived from keyword-only fields.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] The relative ordering of keyword-only parameters is maintained in the re-ordered `__init__()` parameter list.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] If a `field()` specifies a *default_factory*, it is called with zero arguments when a default value for the field is needed.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] If a field is excluded from `__init__()` (using `init=False`) and the field also specifies *default_factory*, then the default factory function will always be called from the generated `__init__()` function.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] This happens because there is no other way to give the field an initial value.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Python stores default member variable values in class attributes.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Note that the two instances of class `C` share the same class variable `x`, as expected.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] This has the same issue as the original example using class `C`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] That is, two instances of class `D` that do not specify a value for `x` when creating a class instance will share the same copy of `x`.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Because dataclasses just use normal Python class creation they also share this behavior.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] There is no general way for Data Classes to detect this condition.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Instead, the `@dataclass` decorator will raise a `ValueError` if it detects an unhashable default parameter.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] The assumption is that if a value is unhashable, it is mutable.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] This is a partial solution, but it does protect against many common errors.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Changed in version 3.11: Instead of looking for and disallowing objects of type `list`, `dict`, or `set`, unhashable objects are now not allowed as default values.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Unhashability is used to approximate mutability.
[src:dataclasses-json/dataclasses] Note that if a field is annotated with a descriptor type, but is not assigned a descriptor object as its default value, the field will act like a normal field.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:dataclasses-json/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:dataclasses-json/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:dataclasses-json/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:dataclasses-json/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:dataclasses-json/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:dataclasses-json/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:dataclasses-json/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:dataclasses-json/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:dataclasses-json/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming can be used to move computations from runtime to compile time, to generate code using compile time computations, and to enable self-modifying code.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] The ability of a programming language to be its own metalanguage allows reflective programming, and is termed *reflection*.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Reflection is a valuable language feature to facilitate metaprogramming.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming was popular in the 1970s and 1980s using list processing languages such as Lisp.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Lisp machine hardware gained some notice in the 1980s, and enabled applications that could process code.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] They were often used for artificial intelligence applications.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming enables developers to write programs and develop code that falls under the generic programming paradigm.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Having the programming language itself as a first-class data type (as in Lisp, Prolog, SNOBOL, or Rebol) is also very useful; this is known as *homoiconicity*.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Generic programming invokes a metaprogramming facility within a language by allowing one to write code without the concern of specifying data types since they can be supplied as parameters when used.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming usually works in one of three ways.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] The second approach is dynamic execution of expressions that contain programming commands, often composed from strings, but can also be from other methods using arguments or context, like JavaScript.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Thus, "programs can write programs." Although both approaches can be used in the same language, most languages tend to lean toward one or the other.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] The third approach is to step outside the language entirely.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] General purpose program transformation systems such as compilers, which accept language descriptions and carry out arbitrary transformations on those languages, are direct implementations of general metaprogramming.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] This allows metaprogramming to be applied to virtually any target language without regard to whether that target language has any metaprogramming abilities of its own.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] One can see this at work with Scheme and how it allows tackling some limits faced in C by using constructs that are part of the Scheme language to extend C.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Lisp is probably the quintessential language with metaprogramming facilities, both because of its historical precedence and because of the simplicity and power of its metaprogramming.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] In Lisp metaprogramming, the unquote operator (typically a comma) introduces code that is evaluated at program definition time rather than at run time.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] The metaprogramming language is thus identical to the host programming language, and existing Lisp routines can be directly reused for metaprogramming if desired.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] This approach has been implemented in other languages by incorporating an interpreter in the program, which works directly with the program's data.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] There are implementations of this kind for some common high-level languages, such as RemObjects’ Pascal Script for Object Pascal.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] This script (or program) generates a new 993-line program that prints out the numbers 1–992.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] This is only an illustration of how to use code to write more code; it is not the most efficient way to print out a list of numbers.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Nonetheless, a programmer can write and execute this metaprogram in less than a minute, and will have generated over 1000 lines of code in that amount of time.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] A quine is a special kind of metaprogram that produces its own source code as its output.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Quines are generally of recreational or theoretical interest only.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Not all metaprogramming involves generative programming.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] One style of generative approach is to employ domain-specific languages (DSLs).
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] One usage of metaprogramming is to instrument programs in order to do dynamic program analysis.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Some argue that there is a sharp learning curve to make complete use of metaprogramming features.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Since metaprogramming gives more flexibility and configurability at runtime, misuse or incorrect use of metaprogramming can result in unwarranted and unexpected errors that can be extremely difficult to debug to an average developer.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] It can introduce risks in the system and make it more vulnerable if not used with care.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Some of the common problems, which can occur due to wrong use of metaprogramming are inability of the compiler to identify missing configuration parameters, invalid or incorrect data can result in unknown exception or different results.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Due to this, some believe that only high-skilled developers should work on developing features which exercise metaprogramming in a language or platform and average developers must learn how to use these features as part of convention.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] The IBM/360 and derivatives had powerful macro assembler facilities that were often used to generate complete assembly language programs or sections of programs (for different operating systems for instance).
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Macros provided with CICS transaction processing system had assembler macros that generated COBOL statements as a pre-processing step.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Other assemblers, such as MASM, also support macros.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] Use of dependent types allows proving that generated code is never invalid.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] However, this approach is leading-edge and rarely found outside of research programming languages.
[src:dataclasses-json/metaprogramming] The list of notable metaprogramming systems is maintained at List of program transformation systems.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] In computer science, a **record** (also called a **structure**, **struct**, **user-defined type (UDT)**, or **compound data type**) is a composite data structure – a collection of fields, possibly of different data types, typically fixed in number and sequence.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] For example, a date could be stored as a record containing a numeric *year* field, a *month* field represented as a string, and a numeric *day-of-month* field.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] A circle record might contain a numeric *radius* and a *center* that is a *point* record containing *x* and *y* coordinates.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Notable applications include the programming language *record type* and for row-based storage, data organized as a sequence of records, such as a database table, spreadsheet or comma-separated values (CSV) file.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] In general, a record type value is stored in memory and row-based storage is in mass storage.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] A *record type* is a data type that describes such values and variables.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Most modern programming languages allow the programmer to define new record types.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] The definition includes specifying the data type of each field and an identifier (name or label) by which it can be accessed.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] In type theory, product types (with no field names) are generally preferred due to their simplicity, but proper record types are studied in languages such as System F-sub.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Since type-theoretical records may contain first-class function-typed fields in addition to data, they can express many features of object-oriented programming.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] In the context of storage such as in a database or spreadsheet a record is often called a *row* and each field is called a column.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] In object-oriented programming, an object is a record that contains state and method fields.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] A record is similar to a mathematical tuple, although a tuple may or may not be considered a record, and vice versa, depending on conventions and the programming language.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] In the same vein, a record type can be viewed as the computer language analog of the Cartesian product of two or more mathematical sets, or the implementation of an abstract product type in a specific language.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] A record differs from an array in that a record's elements (fields) are determined by the definition of the record, and may be heterogeneous whereas an array is a collection of elements with the same type.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] The parameters of a function can be viewed collectively as the fields of a record and passing arguments to the function can be viewed as assigning the input parameters to the record fields.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] At a low-level, a function call includes an *activation record* or *call frame*, that contains the parameters as well as other fields such as local variables and the return address.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] The concept of a record can be traced to various types of tables and ledgers used in accounting since remote times.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] The modern notion of records in computer science, with fields of well-defined type and size, was already implicit in 19th century mechanical calculators, such as Babbage's Analytical Engine.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] The original machine-readable medium used for data (as opposed to control) was the punch card used for records in the 1890 United States census: each punch card was a single record.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Compare the journal entry from 1880 and the punch card from 1895.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Records were well-established in the first half of the 20th century, when most data processing was done using punched cards.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Typically, each record of a data file would be recorded on one punched card, with specific columns assigned to specific fields.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Generally, a record was the smallest unit that could be read from external storage (e.g., card reader, tape, or disk).
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] The contents of punchcard-style records were originally called "unit records" because punchcards had pre-determined document lengths.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] When storage systems became more advanced with the use of hard drives and magnetic tape, variable-length records became the standard.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] A variable-length record is a record in which the size of the record in bytes is approximately equal to the sum of the sizes of its fields.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] This was not possible to do before more advanced storage hardware was invented because all of the punchcards had to conform to pre-determined document lengths that the computer could read, since at the time the cards had to be physically fed into a machine.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Most machine language implementations and early assembly languages did not have special syntax for records, but the concept was available (and extensively used) through the use of index registers, indirect addressing, and self-modifying code.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Some early computers, such as the IBM 1620, had hardware support for delimiting records and fields, and special instructions for copying such records.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] The concept of records and fields was central in some early file sorting and tabulating utilities, such as IBM's Report Program Generator (RPG).
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] COBOL was the first widespread programming language to support record types, and its record definition facilities were quite sophisticated at the time.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] The language allows for the definition of nested records with alphanumeric, integer, and fractional fields of arbitrary size and precision, and fields that automatically format any value assigned to them (e.g., insertion of currency signs, decimal points, and digit group separators).
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Each file is associated with a record variable where data is read into or written from.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] COBOL also provides a `MOVE` `CORRESPONDING` statement that assigns corresponding fields of two records according to their names.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] The early languages developed for numeric computing, such as FORTRAN (up to FORTRAN IV) and ALGOL 60, did not support record types; but later versions of those languages, such as FORTRAN 77 and ALGOL 68 did add them.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] The original Lisp programming language too was lacking records (except for the built-in cons cell), but its S-expressions provided an adequate surrogate.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] The Pascal programming language was one of the first languages to fully integrate record types with other basic types into a logically consistent type system.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] The PL/I language provided for COBOL-style records.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] The C language provides the record concept using structs.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Most languages designed after Pascal (such as Ada, Modula, and Java), also supported records.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Java introduced records in Java 17 and C# introduced records in C#.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Records were introduced to Java to simplify data aggregate classes with less boilerplate, making all fields `final` and `private`, automatically generating all-argument constructors, getters, and the methods `boolean equals()`, `int hashCode()`, and `String toString()`.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Java records all implicitly extend `java.lang.Record`.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Although records are not often used in their original context anymore (i.e. being used solely for the purpose of containing data), records influenced newer object-oriented programming languages and relational database management systems.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Since records provided more modularity in the way data was stored and handled, they are better suited at representing complex, real-world concepts than the primitive data types provided by default in languages.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] This influenced later languages such as C++, Python, JavaScript, and Objective-C which address the same modularity needs of programming.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Objects in these languages are essentially records with the addition of methods and inheritance, which allow programmers to manipulate the way data behaves instead of only the contents of a record.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Many programmers regard records as obsolete now since object-oriented languages have features that far surpass what records are capable of.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] On the other hand, many programmers argue that the low overhead and ability to use records in assembly language make records still relevant when programming with low levels of abstraction.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Today, the most popular languages on the TIOBE index, an indicator of the popularity of programming languages, have been influenced in some way by records due to the fact that they are object oriented.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Query languages such as SQL and Object Query Language were also influenced by the concept of records.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] These languages allow the programmer to store sets of data, which are essentially records, in tables.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] This data can then be retrieved using a primary key.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] The tables themselves are also records which may have a foreign key: a key that references data in another table.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Some languages provide facilities that enumerate the fields of a record.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] This facility is needed to implement certain services such as debugging, garbage collection, and serialization.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] It requires some degree of type polymorphism.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] In contexts that support record subtyping, operations include adding and removing fields of a record.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] A specific record type implies that a specific set of fields are present, but values of that type may contain additional fields.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] A record with fields *x*, *y*, and *z* would thus belong to the type of records with fields *x* and *y*, as would a record with fields *x*, *y*, and *r*.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] The rationale is that passing an (*x*,*y*,*z*) record to a function that expects an (*x*,*y*) record as argument should work, since that function will find all the fields it requires within the record.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Many ways of practically implementing records in programming languages would have trouble with allowing such variability, but the matter is a central characteristic of record types in more theoretical contexts.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Most languages allow assignment between records that have exactly the same record type (including same field types and names, in the same order).
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Depending on the language, however, two record data types defined separately may be regarded as distinct types even if they have exactly the same fields.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] In this alternative, the two operands are still required to have the same sequence of field types.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Some languages may also require that corresponding types have the same size and encoding as well, so that the whole record can be assigned as an uninterpreted bit string.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Other languages may be more flexible in this regard, and require only that each value field can be legally assigned to the corresponding variable field; so that, for example, a short integer field can be assigned to a long integer field, or vice versa.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Other languages (such as COBOL) may match fields and values by their names, rather than positions.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] These same possibilities apply to the comparison of two record values for equality.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Some languages may also allow order comparisons ('<'and '>'), using the lexicographic order based on the comparison of individual fields.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] PL/I allows both of the preceding types of assignment, and also allows *structure expressions*, such as `a = a+1;` where "a" is a record, or structure in PL/I terminology.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] In Algol 68, if `Pts` was an array of records, each with integer fields `X` and `Y`, one could write `Y **of** Pts` to obtain an array of integers, consisting of the `Y` fields of all the elements of `Pts`.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] As a result, the statements `Y **of** Pts[3] := 7` and `(Y **of** Pts)[3] := 7` would have the same effect.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] In Pascal, the command `with R do S` would execute the command sequence `S` as if all the fields of record `R` had been declared as variables.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Similarly to entering a different namespace in an object-oriented language like C#, it is no longer necessary to use the record name as a prefix to access the fields.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] So, instead of writing `Pt.X := 5; Pt.Y := Pt.X + 3` one could write `with Pt do begin X := 5; Y := X + 3 end`.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] The representation of a record in memory varies depending on the programming language.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Often, fields are stored in consecutive memory locations, in the same order as they are declared in the record type.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] This may result in two or more fields stored into the same word of memory; indeed, this feature is often used in systems programming to access specific bits of a word.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] On the other hand, most compilers will add padding fields, mostly invisible to the programmer, in order to comply with alignment constraints imposed by the machine—say, that a floating point field must occupy a single word.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Some languages may implement a record as an array of addresses pointing to the fields (and, possibly, to their names and/or types).
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Objects in object-oriented languages are often implemented in rather complicated ways, especially in languages that allow multiple class inheritance.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] A *self-defining record* is a type of record which contains information to identify the record type and to locate information within the record.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] It may contain the offsets of elements; the elements can therefore be stored in any order or may be omitted.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] The information stored in a self-defining record can be interpreted as metadata for the record, which is similar to what one would expect to find in the UNIX metadata regarding a file, containing information such as the record's creation time and the size of the record in bytes.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Alternatively, various elements of the record, each including an element identifier, can simply follow one another in any order.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] A record, especially in the context of row-based storage, may include **key** fields that allow indexing the records of a collection.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] A primary key is unique throughout all stored records; only one of this key exists.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] In other words, no duplicate may exist for any primary key.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] For example, an employee file might contain employee number, name, department, and salary.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] The employee number will be unique in the organization and will be the primary key.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Depending on the storage medium and file organization, the employee number might be *indexed*—that is also stored in a separate file to make the lookup faster.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] The department code is not necessarily unique; it may also be indexed, in which case it would be considered a *secondary key*, or *alternate key*.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] If it is not indexed, the entire employee file would have to be scanned to produce a listing of all employees in a specific department.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] Keys are usually chosen in a way that minimizes the chances of multiple values being feasibly mapped to by one key.
[src:dataclasses-json/record-computer-science] For example, the salary field would not normally be considered usable as a key since many employees will likely have the same salary.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] When the resulting series of bits is reread according to the serialization format, it can be used to create a semantically identical clone of the original object.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] For many complex objects, such as those that make extensive use of references, this process is not straightforward.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] Serialization of objects does not include any of their associated methods with which they were previously linked.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] This process of serializing an object is also called *marshalling* in some situations.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] The opposite operation, extracting a data structure from a series of bytes, is ***deserialization*** (also called ***unserialization*** or ***unmarshalling***).
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] In networking equipment hardware, the part that is responsible for serialization and deserialization is commonly called SerDes.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] For some of these features to be useful, architecture independence must be maintained.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] For example, for maximal use of distribution, a computer running on a different hardware architecture should be able to reliably reconstruct a serialized data stream, regardless of endianness.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] This means that the simpler and faster procedure of directly copying the memory layout of the data structure cannot work reliably for all architectures.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] Serializing the data structure in an architecture-independent format means preventing the problems of byte ordering, memory layout, or simply different ways of representing data structures in different programming languages.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] Inherent to any serialization scheme is that, because the encoding of the data is by definition serial, extracting one part of the serialized data structure requires that the entire object be read from start to end, and reconstructed.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] In many applications, this linearity is an asset, because it enables simple, common I/O interfaces to be utilized to hold and pass on the state of an object.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] In applications where higher performance is an issue, it can make sense to expend more effort to deal with a more complex, non-linear storage organization.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] Even on a single machine, primitive pointer objects are too fragile to save because the objects to which they point may be reloaded to a different location in memory.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] To deal with this, the serialization process includes a step called *unswizzling* or *pointer unswizzling*, where direct pointer references are converted to references based on name or position.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] The deserialization process includes an inverse step called *pointer swizzling*.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] It is not necessary to actually build the prior copy because differences can be detected on the fly, a technique called differential execution.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] This is useful in the programming of user interfaces whose contents are time-varying — graphical objects can be created, removed, altered, or made to handle input events without necessarily having to write separate code to do those things.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] Serialization breaks the opacity of an abstract data type by potentially exposing private implementation details.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] Trivial implementations which serialize all data members may violate encapsulation.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] To discourage competitors from making compatible products, publishers of proprietary software often keep the details of their programs' serialization formats a trade secret.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] Some deliberately obfuscate or even encrypt the serialized data.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] Yet, interoperability requires that applications be able to understand each other's serialization formats.
