[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] Similarly an object can be read from a stream named s by `(read s)`.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] These two parts of the Lisp implementation are called the Printer and the Reader.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] The output of "`print`" is human readable; it uses lists demarked by parentheses, for example: `(4 2.9 "x" y)`.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] In many types of Lisp, including Common Lisp, the printer cannot represent every type of data because it is not clear how to do so.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] In Common Lisp for example the printer cannot print CLOS objects.
