[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] `Serde` is the most widely used library, or crate, for serialization in Rust which provides the `Serialize` and `Deserialize` traits.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] In general, non-recursive and non-sharing objects can be stored and retrieved in a human readable form using the `storeOn:`/`readFrom:` protocol.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] The `storeOn:` method generates the text of a Smalltalk expression which – when evaluated using `readFrom:` – recreates the original object.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] This scheme is special, in that it uses a procedural description of the object, not the data itself.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] It is therefore very flexible, allowing for classes to define more compact representations.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] However, in its original form, it does not handle cyclic data structures or preserve the identity of shared references (i.e. two references a single object will be restored as references to two equal, but not identical copies).
