[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] There are several ways in Squeak Smalltalk to serialize and store objects.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] The easiest and most used are `storeOn:/readFrom:` and binary storage formats based on `SmartRefStream` serializers.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] In addition, bundled objects can be stored and retrieved using `ImageSegments`.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] Both provide a so-called "binary-object storage framework", which support serialization into and retrieval from a compact binary form.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] Both handle cyclic, recursive and shared structures, storage/retrieval of class and metaclass info and include mechanisms for "on the fly" object migration (i.e. to convert instances which were written by an older version of a class with a different object layout).
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] The APIs are similar (storeBinary/readBinary), but the encoding details are different, making these two formats incompatible.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] However, the Smalltalk/X code is open source and free and can be loaded into other Smalltalks to allow for cross-dialect object interchange.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] Object serialization is not part of the ANSI Smalltalk specification.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] As a result, the code to serialize an object varies by Smalltalk implementation.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] For instance, a serialized object created in Squeak Smalltalk cannot be restored in Ambrai Smalltalk.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] Consequently, various applications that do work on multiple Smalltalk implementations that rely on object serialization cannot share data between these different implementations.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] These applications include the MinneStore object database and some RPC packages.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] A solution to this problem is SIXX, which is a package for multiple Smalltalks that uses an XML-based format for serialization.
[src:dataclasses-json/serialization] The Swift standard library provides two protocols, `Encodable` and `Decodable` (composed together as `Codable`), which allow instances of conforming types to be serialized to or deserialized from JSON, property lists, or other formats.
